  <!-- ===== QUESTION-TYPE FRAMEWORKS ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section" id="frameworks">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Question-Type Frameworks</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">A precision framework for every question type on the H2 Economics paper</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">H2 Economics rewards students who can apply theory to real-world data, draw precise diagrams, and evaluate policies with genuine depth. Here&rsquo;s the specific framework your child uses for each question type &mdash; reverse-engineered from the Cambridge 9570 mark scheme.</p>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">CSQ Data Interpretation &mdash; Extract-Link-Apply</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Case study questions present real-world data &mdash; tables, charts, articles, statistics &mdash; and ask your child to extract meaning from them using economic theory. Most students either describe the data without theory or recite theory without referencing the data. Extract-Link-Apply closes that gap in three moves. Extract: quote a specific figure, trend, or statement from the extract (&lsquo;Table 1 shows that Singapore&rsquo;s inflation rate rose from 1.2% in 2022 to 6.1% in 2023&rsquo;). Link: connect the data to the relevant economic concept (&lsquo;This is consistent with demand-pull inflation driven by an increase in aggregate demand&rsquo;). Apply: explain what the data demonstrates in this specific context (&lsquo;The sharp rise coincided with the post-pandemic recovery, where pent-up demand outpaced the economy&rsquo;s productive capacity&rsquo;). The three moves ensure every case study answer earns both the &lsquo;knowledge&rsquo; and &lsquo;application&rsquo; marks that the mark scheme awards separately.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">CSQ Diagram Questions &mdash; Diagram-First Approach</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">When a case study question asks your child to &lsquo;use a diagram to explain,&rsquo; the diagram is not decoration &mdash; it is the explanation. The Diagram-First Approach means your child draws the diagram before writing a single sentence of text. Step one: identify the correct diagram type (demand-supply, AD-AS, cost curves, exchange rate, Phillips curve, PPC). Step two: draw the initial equilibrium with fully labelled axes, curves, and equilibrium point. Step three: show the change &mdash; shift the relevant curve, mark the new equilibrium, label the change in price/quantity/output. Step four: annotate areas of interest (deadweight loss, consumer surplus, inflationary gap). Only then does your child write the explanation &mdash; and the explanation references the diagram directly (&lsquo;As shown by the leftward shift of AS from AS&#8321; to AS&#8322;...&rsquo;). Cambridge examiners consistently report that the most common reason students score L1 instead of L2 on diagram questions is incomplete labelling, not wrong theory. We drill all 18 core diagrams weekly until every label and arrow is automatic.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Theory Essay &mdash; DEED Structure</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 2 theory essays test whether your child can explain economic mechanisms and evaluate them with depth. DEED gives every essay paragraph a four-part architecture. Define: state the key economic concept in one precise sentence &mdash; not a textbook quote, but a working definition (&lsquo;A negative externality is a cost imposed on third parties not involved in the production or consumption of the good&rsquo;). Explain: lay out the cause-and-effect chain that shows how the concept operates (&lsquo;When a factory emits pollution, nearby residents bear health costs not reflected in the market price, causing the social cost of production to exceed the private cost&rsquo;). Evaluate: challenge the explanation by testing assumptions, identifying limitations, or considering alternative outcomes (&lsquo;This analysis assumes the externality is measurable and that the government has sufficient information to set the optimal tax rate &mdash; conditions rarely met in practice&rsquo;). Diagram: support the explanation with a precisely drawn and fully annotated diagram that drives the argument, not just accompanies it. DEED paragraphs consistently score L2 and above because they demonstrate the &lsquo;knowledge, application, and analysis&rsquo; that the mark scheme requires at every level.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Policy Essay &mdash; DEED + Trade-Off Analysis</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Paper 2 policy essays ask your child to evaluate government interventions &mdash; fiscal policy, monetary policy, supply-side measures, trade policies &mdash; and most students produce a list of advantages and disadvantages without genuine evaluation. DEED + Trade-Off Analysis adds a policy-weighing layer: after the DEED paragraph explains how the policy works, your child evaluates it against three criteria. Effectiveness: does the policy actually achieve its stated objective, and under what conditions? Feasibility: can the government realistically implement this policy given budget constraints, political considerations, and time lags? Equity: does the policy create winners and losers, and are the distributional effects acceptable? Your child then compares alternative policies using the same criteria and arrives at a recommendation &mdash; not &lsquo;a combination of policies is best&rsquo; (the answer that earns zero evaluation marks) but a specific, justified weighting (&lsquo;Expansionary fiscal policy is most effective in the short run given the severity of the recession, but must be complemented by supply-side measures to address the structural unemployment that monetary policy cannot reach&rsquo;). Singapore&rsquo;s unique economic context &mdash; small open economy, no natural resources, MAS-managed exchange rate, CPF system &mdash; is woven into every policy evaluation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Higher-Order Evaluation &mdash; The Evaluation Chain</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">Higher-order evaluation is what separates L2 from L3 in the Cambridge mark scheme &mdash; and it&rsquo;s where most students plateau. The Evaluation Chain teaches your child to layer perspectives systematically rather than writing &lsquo;however, this may not always be the case.&rsquo; Layer one: short-run versus long-run analysis &mdash; does the policy&rsquo;s impact change over time, and if so, how? Layer two: stakeholder analysis &mdash; who benefits and who bears the cost (consumers, producers, government, workers, trading partners)? Layer three: assumption testing &mdash; what must be true for the economic argument to hold, and what happens if those conditions are not met (e.g., demand is assumed to be price elastic, but what if it&rsquo;s inelastic)? Layer four: policy conflicts &mdash; does this policy create trade-offs with other macroeconomic objectives (e.g., expansionary fiscal policy reduces unemployment but may worsen inflation)? Each layer adds evaluative depth that moves the answer up the mark scheme. We practise by marking anonymised peer essays against the actual L1/L2/L3 band descriptors &mdash; so your child learns to recognise what each level looks and reads like.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prog-card">
          <h3 class="prog-card__title">Case Study Evaluation &mdash; Context-Driven Judgement</h3>
          <p class="prog-card__desc">The final parts of each case study question (typically part (e) or (f)) carry the highest marks and demand evaluation &mdash; not just description or explanation. Context-Driven Judgement means your child&rsquo;s evaluation is anchored to the specific case presented, not to generic economic theory. If the case describes a developing economy facing a current account deficit, the evaluation must address that economy&rsquo;s specific constraints (limited fiscal space, weak institutional capacity, dependence on commodity exports) rather than reciting textbook prescriptions. Your child learns to weigh evidence from the extract itself &mdash; using the data provided to support or challenge a policy recommendation &mdash; and to deliver a verdict that specifies conditions: &lsquo;Devaluation would improve the trade balance only if the Marshall-Lerner condition is met, and the data in Table 2 suggests the country&rsquo;s export demand elasticity is low, limiting the policy&rsquo;s effectiveness in the short run.&rsquo; This is the kind of context-specific evaluation that earns the top marks Cambridge reserves for answers demonstrating &lsquo;insightful application to the given context.&rsquo;</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

