      <p class="eyebrow">Before &amp; After</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">The same point, before and after the SHARP Method</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">What changes when a student explains the mechanism instead of stating a result. (Illustrative example &mdash; a single evaluation point, not a real student script.)</p>

      <div class="ba-question">
        <span class="ba-q-label">Essay &middot; Evaluation &middot; &lsquo;Will higher interest rates reduce inflation?&rsquo;</span>
        <p>The point the student wants to make: <em>higher interest rates help control inflation.</em></p>
      </div>

      <div class="ba-grid">
        <div class="ba-card ba-card--before">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--before">Before</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">&ldquo;Higher interest rates reduce inflation because people will spend less money.&rdquo;</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li>States a result with no transmission mechanism</li>
            <li>No diagram</li>
            <li>No evaluation of when it works &mdash; or doesn&rsquo;t</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--before">Level 1</span>
        </div>

        <div class="ba-card ba-card--after">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--after">After SHARP</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">&ldquo;Higher interest rates raise borrowing costs and reward saving, dampening consumption and investment. Lower aggregate demand eases demand-pull inflation (a leftward shift of AD). But the effect depends on how interest-sensitive spending is, works with a time lag, and is weaker against cost-push inflation &mdash; so it is necessary but not always sufficient.&rdquo;</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li><strong>Define &amp; Explain</strong> the transmission mechanism</li>
            <li><strong>Diagram</strong> &mdash; references the AD&ndash;AS shift</li>
            <li><strong>Evaluate</strong> &mdash; limitations and conditions</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--after">Level 3</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="ba-footnote">Illustrative teaching example, not a real student script. Structuring the answer as Define&ndash;Explain&ndash;Evaluate&ndash;Diagram is the <strong>DEED</strong> framework we drill at the <strong>Hit</strong> step of the SHARP Method.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== INSIDE A LESSON ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section lesson-flow" id="lesson-flow">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inside a Lesson</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">What 90 minutes at A-Worthy actually looks like</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__intro">H2 Economics is where memorisation goes to die. Here&rsquo;s exactly how a typical A-Worthy Economics lesson runs &mdash; built around the case study and essay technique that actually move marks.</p>

      <ol class="lesson-timeline">
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">0 &ndash; 5 min &middot; Diagram speed-draw</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Every label, every arrow, automatic</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Five minutes, one diagram from memory &mdash; AD-AS, demand-supply, market failure, exchange rates, or Phillips curve. Students share their attempts on screen. Examiners pay for precise diagrams; we drill until every label, axis and arrow is automatic.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">5 &ndash; 20 min &middot; Case study walkthrough</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Extract, link, apply</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We project a real A-Level case study extract on screen. Students underline data, identify economic concepts and predict the questions before reading them. The <em>Extract-Link-Apply</em> framework turns case studies from data dumps into structured arguments.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">20 &ndash; 40 min &middot; DEED essay framework</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Define, Explain, Evaluate, Diagram</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">DEED &mdash; the four moves that separate Level 3 answers from Level 2. Jeremy demonstrates with one paragraph from a recent A-Level question, then deliberately writes a weak version so students learn to spot what&rsquo;s missing.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">04</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">40 &ndash; 65 min &middot; Live essay writing</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Corrections while the thinking is warm</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students write one full DEED paragraph in real time on a shared document. Jeremy moves between answers and flags issues as they happen &mdash; vague definitions, missing diagrams, evaluation that doesn&rsquo;t actually evaluate. The corrections happen while the thinking is still warm.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">05</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">65 &ndash; 85 min &middot; Mark-scheme breakdown</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Read the mark scheme like an examiner</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We project the SEAB mark scheme alongside two sample answers &mdash; one L2, one L3 &mdash; and identify the exact phrases that earned the upgrade. Learning to read the mark scheme like an examiner is the single biggest mindset shift in Economics.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">06</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">85 &ndash; 90 min &middot; Retrieval set</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Two paragraphs, one diagram, by Friday</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We close by setting two timed paragraphs and one diagram retrieval task, both due before next session. The mark scheme phrases from today get added to a running glossary every student keeps for the year.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="lesson-flow__note">Sessions run weekly via Zoom Pro with cloud recording, so any student who misses a week can catch up before the next one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

